            <fr:title text="The Rieger-Nishimura scheme">The Rieger-Nishimura scheme</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>
  Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {H}[x]]]></fr:tex> be the free Heyting algebra with one generator. The spectrum <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {H}[x]]]></fr:tex> as a topological space is the Rieger-Nishimura laddar,
  
  <html:figure><fr:resource hash="60df66fe9011fe0e2aa3524d84c026e9"><fr:resource-content><html:img src="/60df66fe9011fe0e2aa3524d84c026e9.svg" /></fr:resource-content><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver}]]></fr:resource-source><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
  \begin {tikzcd}
    \bullet  && \bullet  \\
    \bullet  && \bullet  \\
    \bullet  && \bullet  \\
    \bullet  && \bullet  \\
    \vdots  && \vdots  \\
    & \bullet 
    \arrow [from=2-1, to=1-1]
    \arrow [from=2-1, to=1-3]
    \arrow [from=2-3, to=1-3]
    \arrow [from=3-1, to=2-1]
    \arrow [from=3-1, to=2-3]
    \arrow [from=3-3, to=1-1]
    \arrow [from=3-3, to=2-3]
    \arrow [from=4-1, to=3-1]
    \arrow [from=4-1, to=3-3]
    \arrow [from=4-3, to=2-1]
    \arrow [from=4-3, to=3-3]
    \arrow [from=5-1, to=4-1]
    \arrow [from=5-1, to=4-3]
    \arrow [from=5-3, to=3-1]
    \arrow [from=5-3, to=4-3]
    \arrow [from=6-2, to=5-1]
    \arrow [from=6-2, to=5-3]
  \end {tikzcd}
  ]]></fr:resource-source></fr:resource></html:figure>

  It has a unique non-standard <fr:link href="/schm-8ES8/" title="Open subschemes and open immersion" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-8ES8/" display-uri="schm-8ES8" type="local">open subscheme</fr:link>, which we denote as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {H}[x]_+ = \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {H}[x]-\{\bot \}]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bot ]]></fr:tex> is the generic point of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {H}[x]]]></fr:tex>. The open subscheme <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {H}[x]]]></fr:tex> is <html:em>not compact</html:em>, hence it is not affine.
</html:p>
            <html:p>
  In fact, we can compute the global section of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {H}[x]_+]]></fr:tex>. Under <fr:link href="/idem-comm-HLDT/" title="Frame of opens of spectra" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-HLDT/" display-uri="idem-comm-HLDT" type="local">Proposition <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-HLDT/" display-uri="idem-comm-HLDT" /></fr:link>, it as an open subset corresponds to the maximal ideal <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M = \mathbb {H}[x]-\{1\}]]></fr:tex>. This way under <fr:link href="/schm-5L35/" title="Structural sheaf on a general open" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-5L35/" display-uri="schm-5L35" type="local">Proposition <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-5L35/" display-uri="schm-5L35" /></fr:link>,
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \Gamma \mathcal {O}_{\operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {H}[x]_+} \cong  \mathbb {H}[x]_M \cong  \mathbb {H}[x]. ]]></fr:tex>
  The final isomorphism is an easy exercise. This means the open immersion <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {H}[x]_+ \hookrightarrow  \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {H}[x]]]></fr:tex> induces an isomorphism on global section. 
</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
